\chapter{Working with schedules}

In this chapter we describe the module [[nytid.schedules]] that we provide for
working with schedules, indirectly TimeEdit.
We want to be able to use the course schedule and the personal schedules
provided by TimeEdit.

The idea is as follows.
We'll use the [[icalendar]] package to handle events and schedules
(calendars).
This means that we can use the ICS exports from TimeEdit, Google Calendar etc.

\paragraph{Why \texttt{icalendar} and not \texttt{ics}}

Earlier versions of nytid used the [[ics]] package (version 0.7).
Its parser turned out to be the single dominant cost of
[[nytid schedule show]]: parsing a real external feed of 2\,194\,963
characters (2.2\,MB, 3709 events) took \emph{26.33 seconds}, of which
about 95 percent was spent inside [[ics.grammar]]'s generated TatSu
PEG parser tokenizing the 48\,000 content lines---roughly 1.5
milliseconds per line.
The effect was that a calendar-cache hit and a network fetch were
indistinguishable to the user: the parse dominated both.
The [[icalendar]] package parses the same feed in \emph{1.17 seconds},
22 times faster, which makes the on-disk text cache
(\cref{CachingExternalCalendars}) actually pay off.

Speed is not the only reason.
The [[ics]] package cannot expand recurring events ([[RRULE]]), so a
weekly meeting in an external feed appeared only once, at its first
occurrence---the same real feed above contains 227 [[RRULE]]s.
The [[icalendar]] package has the actively maintained companion
package [[recurring-ical-events]] for exactly this.
Finally, [[ics]] 0.7 is effectively unmaintained and forced two extra
dependencies on us: [[arrow]] (its timestamp type) and [[tatsu]] (its
parser generator); with [[icalendar]] we use plain
[[datetime.datetime]] from the standard library.


