\section{Representing events}

We will use the ICS calendar format to represent events.
For this we will use the [[icalendar]] package.
Events are [[icalendar.Event]] objects; their start and end times are
plain [[datetime.datetime]] objects, exposed through the [[.start]]
and [[.end]] properties.
We keep all event datetimes timezone aware (\cref{ParsingCalendars}
establishes this invariant at parse time), so events from different
sources can always be compared and sorted.
<<imports>>=
import calendar
import datetime
import icalendar
@ Using the [[icalendar]] package allows us to work with calendar related
things in a standard way, so that we later can just import calendars through
[[.ics]] files.

When we print such an object, it will print the ICS formatted version.
This is useful for creating [[.ics]] files, but not for pretty-printing the 
schedule to the terminal.
We introduce formatting functions for that purpose.


\subsection{Formatting event headers}

The event header is a compact one-line summary used by every other formatting
function.
We factor it out so that [[format_event_short]] and [[format_event]] both
produce consistent headers without duplicating the date/time logic.
The [[week]] flag is the only source of variation between the two callers: the
short format defaults to no week info (one line stays terse), while the long
format defaults to including it (more context for reading a full event).

Every field of the header---week number, weekday, date and
time---derives from one [[astimezone]]-converted local timestamp.
Deriving them from the event's stored timestamp instead would mix
timezones: feeds typically store UTC, so an event at 00:30 local time
on a Monday is stored as Sunday 23:30 and would display Monday's time
next to \emph{Sunday's} weekday and week number.
<<functions>>=
def format_header(event, week=True):
    """
    Formats the event header, a one-line representation (week, date, time,
    event title)

    If the `week` parameter is `True` (default), the week number and weekday
    will be included in the header.
    """
    header = ""
    local_start = event.start.astimezone()

    if week:
      header += f"Week {local_start.isocalendar()[1]} " \
                + calendar.day_name[local_start.weekday()] + " "

    header += local_start.strftime('%d/%m %H:%M')

    header += f" {event.summary}"

    return header
@


\subsection{Testing [[format_header]]}

The header includes week number, weekday, date/time, and event name when
[[week=True]].
Without week info, only date/time and name remain.
This contrast clarifies the effect of the [[week]] parameter.
<<test functions>>=
def test_format_header_with_week():
  event = make_event()
  header = format_header(event, week=True)
  assert "Week 3" in header
  assert "Monday" in header
  assert event.summary in header

def test_format_header_without_week():
  event = make_event()
  header = format_header(event, week=False)
  assert "Week" not in header
  assert "Monday" not in header
  assert event.summary in header
  assert "15/01" in header
