The interesting case is an event whose stored timezone and the local
timezone disagree about the date: stored as Sunday 23:30 UTC, it
takes place after midnight local time in any timezone east of UTC.
The weekday and date in the header must be the \emph{local} ones, the
same day as the displayed time.
We compute the expected values from the converted timestamp rather
than hard-coding them, so the test passes in any test machine
timezone---and still fails if the implementation regresses to the
stored timezone, since the assertion always demands local values.
<<test functions>>=
def test_format_header_weekday_matches_local_date():
  event = make_event(begin="2024-01-14T23:30:00+00:00",
                     end="2024-01-15T00:30:00+00:00")
  local = event.start.astimezone()
  header = format_header(event, week=True)
  assert calendar.day_name[local.weekday()] in header
  assert local.strftime('%d/%m') in header
