\section{Handling calendars from URLs and files}

\subsection{Parsing ICS text}
\label{ParsingCalendars}

All ICS text---fetched, cached or read from file---is parsed through
one function, so that the parser is also the single place where we can
establish an invariant about the resulting events: \emph{every parsed
event has timezone-aware [[datetime.datetime]] start and end values}.

The ICS format does not guarantee this by itself.
All-day events carry date values ([[DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20240115]]),
which [[icalendar]] faithfully returns as [[datetime.date]]; and
\enquote{floating} times (no [[Z]] suffix, no [[TZID]]) come back as
naive datetimes.
Both would poison every comparison downstream: sorting a mix of dates
and datetimes raises [[TypeError]], as does comparing naive against
aware datetimes.
Rather than teaching every consumer to handle three kinds of values,
we normalize here: dates become local midnight, naive times are
interpreted as local time.
Local is the right reading for both---an all-day event on the 15th
means the 15th in the user's calendar, not in UTC.
<<functions>>=
def parse_calendar(text):
  """
  Parses ICS text into an `icalendar.Calendar`.

  Normalizes all events so that their start and end values are
  timezone-aware `datetime.datetime` objects: all-day events (date
  values) become local midnight, naive times are interpreted as local
  time. Raises ValueError if `text` is not valid ICS.
  """
  cal = icalendar.Calendar.from_ical(text)
  for event in cal.events:
    for name in ("DTSTART", "DTEND"):
      <<normalize the [[name]] property of [[event]]>>
  return cal
@

The normalization rewrites the property through [[Event.add]], since
[[icalendar]] components store encoded property objects rather than
bare datetimes.
The [[datetime]]-before-[[date]] test order matters:
[[datetime.datetime]] is a subclass of [[datetime.date]], so testing
[[date]] first would match everything.
<<normalize the [[name]] property of [[event]]>>=
value = event.get(name)
if value is None:
  continue
if isinstance(value.dt, datetime.datetime):
  if value.dt.tzinfo is None:
    del event[name]
    event.add(name, value.dt.astimezone())
elif isinstance(value.dt, datetime.date):
  midnight = datetime.datetime(value.dt.year, value.dt.month,
                               value.dt.day).astimezone()
  del event[name]
  event.add(name, midnight)
@

Let's verify the invariant for the three cases: aware values pass
through, all-day dates become aware local midnight, and naive times
become aware:
<<test functions>>=
def test_parse_calendar_all_day_event():
  text = """BEGIN:VCALENDAR
VERSION:2.0
PRODID:-//Test//Test//EN
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:All day
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20240115
DTEND;VALUE=DATE:20240116
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR"""
  cal = parse_calendar(text)
  event = cal.events[0]
  assert isinstance(event.start, datetime.datetime)
  assert event.start.tzinfo is not None
  assert event.start.date() == datetime.date(2024, 1, 15)

def test_parse_calendar_naive_time():
  text = """BEGIN:VCALENDAR
VERSION:2.0
PRODID:-//Test//Test//EN
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Floating
DTSTART:20240115T100000
DTEND:20240115T120000
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR"""
  cal = parse_calendar(text)
  event = cal.events[0]
  assert event.start.tzinfo is not None
  assert event.start.hour == 10

def test_parse_calendar_aware_time():
