\subsection{Clearing the cache}
\label{ClearingTheCache}

Sometimes the user knows the cached copies are wrong---a course was
rescheduled, or a feed URL started serving different content---and
waiting out the TTL is not an option.
The user-facing command [[nytid schedule external clear-cache]] wraps
this function.
We return the number of removed files so the CLI can report what
happened.
A missing cache directory simply means there is nothing to remove:
[[glob]] on a non-existent directory yields nothing.
<<functions>>=
def clear_cache():
  """
  Deletes all cached external ICS files.
  Returns the number of files removed.
  """
  removed = 0
  for path in cache_dir().glob("*.ics"):
    path.unlink()
    removed += 1
  return removed
@

Let's verify both the populated and the empty case:
<<test functions>>=
def test_clear_cache_removes_files(tmp_path, monkeypatch):
  monkeypatch.setattr("nytid.schedules.cache_dir", lambda: tmp_path)
  for number in range(3):
    (tmp_path / f"{number}.ics").write_text("data")

  assert clear_cache() == 3
  assert list(tmp_path.glob("*.ics")) == []

def test_clear_cache_missing_dir(tmp_path, monkeypatch):
  monkeypatch.setattr("nytid.schedules.cache_dir",
                      lambda: tmp_path / "absent")
  assert clear_cache() == 0
@


\section{Filtering events}

We filter events using a whitelist rather than a blacklist.
A blacklist would require us to enumerate every non-teaching event type that
TimeEdit might produce---but TimeEdit adds new activity types over time,
so a blacklist would silently admit unknown types.
A whitelist is conservative: an unknown type is excluded until explicitly
added, which is the safer failure mode when the filtered list feeds into a
sign-up sheet.

Within the whitelist we match using a regex anchored to the start of the
event name, with a word-boundary suffix [[(,|\s|$)]].
A plain [[in]]-check would cause \enquote{Exam} to match
\enquote{Examinationsdag}; the anchored regex prevents that by requiring the
match to end at a comma, whitespace, or end-of-string---the separators
TimeEdit uses when appending course codes to activity names.
<<functions>>=
def event_filter(events, whitelisted=TIMEEDIT_EVENTS):
  """
  Takes a list of events (icalendar.Event), returns a filtered list of events
  (generator). The events to include are the teaching events.

  It covers the following events:

    <<whitelisted events>>
  """
  for event in events:
    for event_type in whitelisted:
      if re.match(f"^{event_type}(,|\\s|$)", event.summary):
        yield event
        break
<<imports>>=
import re
@

